observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Direct the Accounting Office to:
Determine the applicable guidelines relative to the fund transfers for prizes amounting ₱1.031 million from Due to NGAs and ₱25,000.00 from Due to LGUs by coordinating with the respective agencies for proper treatment and reclassification of the funds;
Conduct a detailed review of the unliquidated balance of ₱36,000.00 from (Department of Environment and Natural Resources) DENR and coordinate with the source agency to confirm the validity, purpose, and status of the funds. If the fund is determined to be stale, untraceable, or no longer valid, initiate the refund or write-off process in accordance with the procedures prescribed under applicable COA issuances;
Conduct thorough tracing of the transaction	related to the retention money funded by DOH-CVCHD amounting to ₱64,010.00 to determine its intended payee and the specific project to which it pertains. Upon verification, reclassify the amount to its appropriate account, “Guaranty/Security Deposits Payable,” in accordance with accounting standards. In the event that the transaction cannot be substantiated and the rightful payee cannot be identified, initiate the process for the refund of the amount to the source agency following existing government accounting and auditing rules;
Coordinate with DA-RO2 to obtain the MOAs for the two projects transferred in 2003 and 2004. If unavailable, formally request a certified copy or a notarized statement from the agency explaining the status of the agreements;
Strictly adhere to Sections 4.6 and 4.9 of COA Circular No. 94-013 by ensuring the preparation of Liquidation Reports on a monthly basis for all received funds, regardless of whether transactions have occurred, and promptly submit within the prescribed period to this Office and the respective Source Agencies. Also, indicate the Source Agency, date prepared, and proper report number in all Liquidation Reports to ensure completeness, traceability, and audit trail integrity. Relative thereto, assign personnel to monitor the timely submission of the same; and
Strengthen financial monitoring mechanisms by conducting periodic reconciliations with Source Agencies to ensure that reported balances are accurate and up to date.
Require the personnel in-charge in the review and monitoring of commitments and agreements with partner-agencies to clearly specify project implementation timelines, including the start date, completion date, and reporting deadlines, to prevent delays and promote efficient fund utilization. Additionally, ensure that the date of signing by both parties is explicitly indicated in the MOA and notarized. A clear copy of the signed MOA be submitted to the Office of the Auditor for proper monitoring and reference.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Inventory Committee to analyze the nature of the items included in the RPCPPE and classify them according to the appropriate and specific PPE account titles prescribed in the Revised Chart of Accounts;
Require the Inventory Committee and Municipal Accountant to reconcile the inventory count report and the accounting records. Investigate and evaluate the differences, adjust the records as appropriate and submit a revised RPCPPE based on the reconciliations made;
Direct the Agency’s disposal committee to initiate the disposal procedures for the unserviceable property identified which shall be reported in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP); and
Prioritize the strict implementation and enforcement of the documentary and procedural requirements of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

We recommended that Management:
Include as a priority project the establishment of a room/building which shall serve as the storage facility for procured property and inventories prior to the release to end-user units. Relative to this, Management shall endeavor to maintain a centralized inventory management system;
Pending the establishment of a storage room/warehouse, the Municipal Mayor shall designate employees, who shall be properly bonded, to manage the issuance, recording and reporting of inventories in their respective offices;
Require the proper utilization of the stock cards at the office-level in the monitoring of supplies and materials;
Require the Agency’s Inventory Committee together with the representatives from the end-user units and the General Services Officer to conduct an inventory count on all office supplies that are yet to be consumed as of a cut-off date to be determined by the Committee and prepare a Report on Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) for recording and control purposes. Henceforth, conduct the required physical count and submit to the Auditor the report thereon not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
Based on the RPCI prepared, the Municipal Accountant shall prepare an entry to recognize the cost of Inventories at hand and henceforth observe the proper accounting policies and entries in the recording of transactions; and
Ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage.

We recommended that Management:
Submit explanation/justification with verifiable basis why disbursements on procurements which were noted as non-compliant with existing procurement law, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements for the procurement of goods and services are included and updated in the end-user PPMP and Agency APP by requiring a certification to that effect from the Head of the BAC Secretariat, who shall, based on the submissions of the end-user units, validate such fact;
Henceforth, require the BAC to submit the proof of validation on the technical, legal and financial capability of the suppliers together with Mayor’s Permit and proof of PhilGEPs Registration on all purchases made through Alternative Mode of Procurement to support eligibility of suppliers;
Instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to specify in the Request for Quotation (RFQ) under the General Instructions portion the evaluation method for submitted bids and indicating whether the contract will be awarded on a per item, whole lot, or by several lots. Subsequently, ensure that the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC) reflected in the RFQ accurately corresponds to the chosen bid evaluation method, providing comprehensive information to interested bidder-suppliers about the bid ceiling;
Direct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that posting requirements of RFQ, Notice of Award, Purchase Order/Contract and Notice to Proceed, if necessary, on all procurement through shopping with ABC higher than P50,000.00 are complied with and proof thereof are attached to the disbursement voucher to establish correctness of information and reliability of bidding process; and
Ensure that all regulatory permits, registrations and licenses are available and up-to-date prior to engaging the services of individuals and businesses. If unavailable, encourage the prospective suppliers to secure permits and comply other registration requirements such as Mayor’s Permit, BIR and PhilGEPS registrations etc., to ensure eligibility in future procurement endeavors with the LGU-Ivana.

We recommended that Management:
Ensure that PPAs funded out of the DRRM funds are well-planned and meticulously reviewed by the LDRRMC. Accordingly, intensive procurement planning and coordination with stakeholders and regulating agencies shall be conducted prior to the inclusion of PPAs in the LDRRMP and LDRRMFIP;
Require the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Officer, in coordination with the implementing offices, to strictly monitor the implementation of the programs, projects and activities (PPAs) and formulate catch-up plans for slow to non-moving PPAs to avoid further delays in the implementation and facilitate the timely completion thereof;
Require the implementing office, in coordination with Bids and Awards Committee for purposes of monitoring compliance, to timely identify the component items of the crafted PPAs and religiously submit the corresponding PPMPs to the BAC Secretariat for consolidation or updating of APP, to prevent LDRRM Funds to became idle, thus, maximum utilization can be achieved.
Utilize the stock card in the inventory management to ensure that welfare goods are available and in optimal condition when required. Similarly, ensure the timely and proper disposal of nearly expiring goods/items through the identified modality by the LGU, to preclude any wastage of government funds; and
Ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage.

We recommended that Management:
require the Inventory Committee and OIC-Municipal Accountant to reconcile the inventory count report and the accounting records. Investigate and evaluate the differences, adjust the records as appropriate and submit a revised RPCPPE based on the reconciliations made;
require the Inventory Committee to analyze the nature of the items included in the RPCPPE and classify them according to the appropriate and specific PPE account titles prescribed in the Revised Chart of Accounts;
direct the Agency’s disposal committee to initiate the disposal procedures for the unserviceable property identified which shall be reported in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP);
require the Inventory Committee and Municipal Accountant to identify the PPE items that failed to meet the P15,000.00 capitalization threshold and the latter shall prepare appropriate adjusting entries based  on verifiable evidence; and
prioritize the strict implementation and enforcement of the documentary and procedural requirements of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

We recommended the following courses of actions:

The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant and General Services Office  with the complete description and cost segregation of road component for road projects;
